JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1577
EP  - 1597
VL  - 66
IS  - 4
KW  - inequality
KW  - taste-based inequality
KW  - social preferences
KW  - impartial spectator
KW  - experiment
KW  - merit
KW  - luck
KW  - subjective
KW  - perceptions
KW  - income
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12770
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT Many economic allocation decisions involve subjective judgment. This judgment may be perceived as fair when needs are considered but may seem unjust in cases of personal-taste discrimination. In an experimental impartial-spectator design, we explore perceptions of taste-based inequality and compare them to attitudes toward inequalities grounded in objective procedures, namely, merit and luck. We find that while taste-based inequality is perceived distinctly, it is treated as unfair, similar to luck and unlike merit. Additionally, our work suggests that the perception of merit as more fair than luck is primarily driven by individuals with above-average income.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Fed's Discount Window in “Normal” Times
AU  - Ennis, Huberto M.
AU  - Klee, Elizabeth
Y1  - 2025/10/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12772
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1459
EP  - 1485
VL  - 66
IS  - 4
KW  - banking
KW  - central bank
KW  - Federal Reserve
KW  - liquidity
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12772
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT We study banks' use of the Fed's discount window during a time of relative calm in financial markets. We merge transaction-level data on discount window borrowings with quarterly bank balance sheet information between 2010 and 2019. We develop a model of the borrowing decisions of banks and contrast its implications with the data. In line with the model, we find that discount window borrowing is tightly linked to the composition of banks' balance sheets. Importantly, banks holding less reserves are more likely to borrow from the discount window, as are banks with more expensive and fragile liabilities, and less marketable collateral.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Unemployment-Risk Channel in Business-Cycle Fluctuations
AU  - Broer, Tobias
AU  - Druedahl, Jeppe
AU  - Harmenberg, Karl
AU  - Öberg, Erik
Y1  - 2025/10/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12773
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1425
EP  - 1458
VL  - 66
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12773
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT The unemployment-risk channel (URC) amplifies an initial contraction through a reduction in consumption demand by workers who fear unemployment. Crucial for this are the dynamics of job separations and firm hiring. In US data, the job-finding rate responds slower to identified macroeconomic shocks than the separation rate, but accounts for a similar share of the unemployment response. We calibrate a tractable heterogeneous-agent new-Keynesian model with endogenous separations and sluggish vacancy creation to match these facts. The share of output fluctuations due to the URC is twice as large as in a standard model with exogenous separations and free entry.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Life-Cycle Wage Growth and Internal Migration
AU  - Rivera-Padilla, Alberto
Y1  - 2025/10/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12775
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1505
EP  - 1523
VL  - 66
IS  - 4
KW  - human capital
KW  - internal migration
KW  - productivity
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12775
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT I document new facts on life-cycle wage growth within three countries: Brazil, Mexico, and the United States. In every case, I find that experience?wage profiles are steeper in rich states. Differences in education and industry mix can account for a large share of the covariance between income and profile steepness in both developing countries, while differences in occupations are key in every case. Using a general equilibrium model, I estimate meaningful productivity gains from inducing migration to places with better learning environment and find that migration costs are important in explaining cross-country differences in life-cycle wage growth.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bargaining Foundations for Price Taking in Matching Markets
AU  - Elliott, Matthew
AU  - Talamàs, Eduard
Y1  - 2025/10/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12776
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1561
EP  - 1575
VL  - 66
IS  - 4
KW  - bargaining
KW  - investment incentives
KW  - matching markets
KW  - price taking
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12776
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT Agents make noncontractible investments before bargaining over who matches with whom and their terms of trade. An agent is a price taker when her investments do not change her potential partners' payoffs. This incentivizes socially optimal investments. Across a variety of noncooperative bargaining models featuring dynamic entry, we show that everyone necessarily becomes a price taker as the discount factor goes to 1 if there is a minimal amount of competition always present in the market. If this condition is not satisfied, dynamic entry need not create enough competition to guarantee price taking even if agents are arbitrarily patient.
ER  - 

