SP  - 1713
EP  - 1732
VL  - 66
IS  - 4
KW  - bilateral migration
KW  - brain drain
KW  - brain gain
KW  - economic development
KW  - human capital
KW  - inequality
KW  - international migration
KW  - migration costs
KW  - selective emigration
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12779
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT International migration is a selective process with ambiguous effects on human capital and economic development in sending countries. We establish the theoretical microfoundations of the relationship between selective emigration and human capital accumulation in a multicountry context. We embed this migration?education nexus into a development accounting framework to quantify the effects of migration on development and inequality. Selective emigration stimulates human capital accumulation and income in most origin countries. The effect varies according to the level of development, the dyadic structure of migration costs, and education policies. Emigration significantly reduces the number of people living in extreme poverty.
ER  - 

