VL  - 66
IS  - 4
KW  - income segregation
KW  - income sorting
KW  - mass transit
KW  - public transportation
KW  - residential location
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70008
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT What are the implications of mass transit improvements for residential income segregation within cities? I observe large income differences in households' usage of and residential proximity to ?fast? versus ?slow? transit (e.g., subways vs. buses on shared lanes). Consistent with these observations, I propose a theoretical framework to characterize the relationship between income segregation and the spatial distribution of transit speeds and travel mode choices within cities. I find that transit improvements that would maximize transit ridership tend to reduce income segregation when improving ?slow? transit but increase income segregation when improving ?fast? transit.
ER  - 

